{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_lily_ver01/data/sn78002169/00279558868/1945101401/0540.xml":{"full_text":"TJ*e Sunday Star-News\nPublished Every Sunday\nBy The Wilmington Star-News\nR. B. Page. Publisher\nTelephone All Departments 2-3311\nEntered as Second Class Matter at Wilming\nton, N. C.. Postoffice Under Act of Congress\n_of March 3, 1878.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES BY CARRIER\nIN NEW HANOVER COUNTY\nPayable Weekly or In Advance\nCombi\nTime Star News nation\n1 Week __f .30 .25 S .51\ni Month 1.30 1.10\n3 Montha- 3.80 3.25 B.50\n6 Months_ 7.80 6.50 13.00\nl year _ 15.60 13.00 26.00\n(Above rates entitle subscriber to Sunday\nIssue of Star-Ncwa)_\nBy Mall: Payable Strictly in Advance\n3 Months _-4 2.50 2.00 3.85\n6 Months _\u2014 5.00 4.00 7.70\n1 year _ 10.00 8.00 15.40\n(Above rates entitle subscriber to Sunday\nissue of Star-News)_\nWILMINGTON STAR\n(Daily Without Sunday) __\nI Months-31.65 6 Months-$3.70 1 Yr.->7.40\nWhen remitting by mail please use checks or\nU. S. P. O. money order. The Star-News can\nnot be responsible for currency sent through\nthe mails.\nMEMBER OF THE ASSOCIATED PRESS\nAND ALSO SERVED BY THE UNITED PRESS\nSUNDAY, OCTOBER 14, 1945\nTOP O\u2019 THE MORNING\nIt was not what people saw in Christ\nas a healer of men\u2019s bodies that filled\nthem with the deepest wonder and drew\nhardest upon their hearts: it was what\nthey saw in Him as the Physician of Souls.\nWho is this that even forgiveth sins?\u201d\nThe world had seen healers of bodies be\nfore; but here was one who coSfd go down\nthe depths where human hearts ache and\nthere perform His miracle of healing as\neasily as He could heal the bodies of men.\n\u2014Pell.\nThe War Created An Asset\nA war-created asset is that tens of thousands\nof persons throughout the country know of Wil\nmington\u2019s existence than ever did before. Un\nconsciencely on the part of the permanent pop\nulation, the city and its environment have\nreceived publicity that could not have been\naccomplished by, say, a million-dollar adver\ntising campaign.\nAnd the best of it is that the great majority\nof these thousands, in learning of the city,\nmany by visits to trainees at Camp Davis or\nby employment, have formed a favorable im\npression both of the community and its people.\nThe growlers are in the minority, and for the\nmcsc part would be dissatisfied in Elysium.\nWhat, then, shall Wilmington do to take best\nadvantage of the situation, not for its own\n\u00bba..3 alone but for those among these thous\nands who would like to return and become\ndweiiers in our midst? Employment, of course,\nis a primary provision. This is being built up\nthrough the attraction of new industries which,\nthough small, will in the aggregate provide\nmany jobs.\nThe next enterprise that ought to be under\ntaken is adequate housing. A new hotel would\nhelp. And a downtown efficiency apartment\nhouse would be invaluable. More retail business\non Third street, which is not so subject to traf\nfic jams, would be welcomed by shoppers.\nThe street\u2019s width alone would give it advan\ntages not enjoyed elsewhere in the city except\non Market street, which would be under handi\ncap by the grade between Third and Fourth.\nIt also seems that exploitation of a greater\ndiversity of opportunities would be well ad\nvised. In addition to new and existing indus\ntries, and port development, Wilmington could\ntell more about its many churches and its\nschool system which, but for the lack of a\njunior college, is as fine as can be found\nanywhere.\nThe chance to have a junior college, which\nwas so blindly rejected by the count;\nmission when last brought up, is stih\nard should be seized without further lo__ of\ntime, so that another school year need not\nstart without it.\nYesterday we noted the opportunity in agri\nculture, which cannot be over-emphasized.\nThe postwar period finds Wilmington in a\nbetter situation to move ahead than it has ever\nenjoyed. The only need is for the community\u2019s\nleadership to take advantage of it.\nBanks Well Fixed\nThe start of the peacetime period finds the\nnation\u2019s banking system stronger than ever\nbefore. Earnings have been in a rising trend\nfor six years. Substantial reserves have been\nbuilt up. The rate of return on capital funds\nhas reached an all-time high. This informaton\nis given by United Business Service of Boston,\nwhich adds:\n\"Although there will be some shifting of de\nposits during the transition period, total depos\nits are expected to hold near present record\nlevels. Banks will take over a large part of\nshort-term Government bonds now held by\nbusiness firms, and will buy obligations used\nto replace War Bonds cashed in by consumers.\nA return flow of money in circulation is also\nlikely. Commercial loans will probably expand,\n^d mortgage money and other consumer\njtfcdit will be in increasing demand. The de\nposits created by these transactions will swell\nthe earnings potential of the banks.\n\u2018\u2018The probability of lower tax rates next year\nIs also a bullish factor for banks. Taxes in\nrecent years have been taking an increasing\nproportion of tax exempt securities has been\nused up their available tax losses, and their\nproportion of tax exempt securtes has been\ndropping rapidly.\n\u2018\u2018Because of the desirability of building up\ncapital funds, which are now very low in rela\ntion to deposits, the conservative dividend pol\ncicies of recent years will probably- be con\ntinued. This plowing back of earnings has re\nsulted in a sizable gain in book values, a fac\ntor which is important in appraising bank\nStocks. As earnings improve in coming years,\nlarger payment* to shareholders may be ex\nl\nBridge Projects Welcome\nReplacement of the bridges over the Bruns\nwick river and Allegator creek on highway\nNo. 17, which is to be undertaken in the near\nfuture, according to word from the division\nengineer, C. E. Brown, at Fayetteville, will\nbe a step forward in travel safety.\nHighway No. 17 carries a heavy traffic load\nall the year\u2014has done so even during the\nwar years\u2014and with improvement in the gaso\nline situation and liberalization of tire restric\ntons more and more motor vehicles are using\nit. As the most direct route from this Seaboard\nterritory to Jacksonville, where it merges with\nhighways down the east and the west Florida\ncoasts, and provides connections with main\ntraveled roads in South Carolina and Georgia\nen route, it is naturally sought out not only\nby motorists in private cars and traveling\nmen who again may cover their territories by\nauto instead of train or bus, but also by\ntrucks in commercial transport.\nIts improvement therefore becomes a pri\nmary necessity in the highway program, both\nfor the comfort and convience of its users\nand the reduction of accident hazards.\nThe Brunswick and Allegator bridges have\nlong been major hazards because of their nar\nrowness. Careful drivers have for years made\nit their practice to stop at the approaches\nwhen other vehicles were coming across, wait\ning until the way was clear. Less careful driv\ners or others not familiar with the situaton\nhave in most cases been able to squeeze by,\nbut several serious accidents have happened\non both bridges. The work to be done on them\nwill provide wider traffic lanes in addition to\nmaking them more secure. It is a welcome\nproject.\nHard To Understand Reds\nRussian psychology becomes more difficult\nto understand almost daily. Better understand\ning is not aided by an article in the Soviet\ngovernment newspaper Izvestia, in which that\njournal\u2019s \u201cInternational Observer\u201d accuses\nwhat he calls Europe\u2019s \u201cwestern bloc\u201d of seek\ning to separate the peaceloving nations and\nsow the \u201cseeds of war.\u201d\nConcerning the recent conference of Foreign\nMinisters in London he cites excerpts from\nthe foreign press to support his contention\nthat the Russians took the correct stand at\nthe Council sessions. He emphasizes comment\nin the New Statesman and Nation, a British\npublication, which is said to have declared\nthe \u201cmabi object of the west bloc is economic\nprotection against American capitalism, which\nis actively trying to reduce England to a state\nof vassalage.\u201d And he comments: \u201cWhether\nthe west bloc is primarily anti-American or\nAnti-Soviet, it retains its negative character,\nbeing directed toward splitting the peaceloving\nnations and sowing tile seeds of war.\u201d\nThe United Press, reporting from Moscow,\nadds:\nSumming up Anglo-American press reaction\nto the Foreign Ministers\u2019 Council meeting, the\n\u201cObserver\u201d said that \u201clone voices in America\npointed out that the conference met in cir\ncumstances of the activization of forces hostile\nto the Soviet Union.\u201d\nThe Russian newspaper writer mentioned\nJohannes Steel, American commentator, as\nauthority for this statement. He quoted Mr.\nSteel as having said that the \u201csame forces\nthat tried to use Germany in a world crusade\nagainst the Soviet Union are active again.\u201d\n\u201cThe same pressure as was then applied on\nofficial persons now is evident,\u201d the writer\nsaid Mr. Steel declared.\nHe then pointed out that Japan and Ger\nmany bad been defeated and added:\n\u201cReactionary forces that cannot reconcile\nthemselves to the fact that the Soviet Union\nemerged from the war not weaker but stronger\nthan ever can hardly expect to succeed in\nvicious anti-Soviet intrigues.\u201d\nThe article cited the letter of Laborite Par\nliament Member David Pritt to The Times of\nLondon defending the Soviet position at the\nForeign Ministers\u2019 Council, asserting that the\ninterests of the small and great nations alike\ndemanded that the Big Three powers \u201cmake\nthe most important decisions, and that the\nprinciples of the Berlin Conference prevail,\ngiving a decisive voice to the parties directly\nonnfPrnpH\nIt said that a New York Herald Tribune\neditorial regretted that the United States had\ntaken the initiative in terminating the London\nConference while the Soviet Union had wished\nto continue it.\n\u201cSuch admissions prove that the facts can\nnot be disregarded,\u201d said The Izvestia writer.\n\u201cSooner or later all critics of Soviet behavior\nat the London Conference must recognize this.\u201d\nThe news that has come from Russian\nsources ever since and even before the German\ncapitulation has shown that the Soviet Uniom\nhas been the chief threat to peace and suggests\nthat as long as the present Foreign Minister,\nMr. Molotov, holds that office will continue\nin this role.\nIt is time that Moscow stopped its constant\nheckling and took its proper place in the peace\ninstead of trying to dominate it and claiming\nthat it alone is right.\nNo football contest, says Grandpappy\nJenkins, is as tough as the scramble to find\nthe place where you parked your car before\nthe game.\n\nThe worker bee has 3,000 to 4,000 eyes, ac\ncording to Factographs. Gosh, after a hard\nday\u2019s work the bags under \u2019em must be plenty\ncrowded.\n\nGeologists predict 65 years of fair weather.\nThe only hitch to that, points out Zadok\nDumkopf, they didn\u2019t say when they would\nstart.\n\nNow that woven wood has been made prac\ntical it\u2019s feared Mother wan\u2019t be satisfied with\njust moving the furniture around. She\u2019ll prob\nably want to reknit it, too\nDrastic May Bill\nBY ARTHUR KROCK\nWASHINGTON, Oct. 13.\u2014\u201cThe Atomic En\nergy Act of 1945,\u201d drafted by the adminis\ntration and introduced by Representative\nMay, grants peacetime powers to Government\nofficials and imposes restrictions on private\nscientific research and manufacture beyond\nany provided in the legislative history of this\ncountry, even when limited to the period of\nwar. Thus, the first effects of the creation\nof the atomic bomb by citizens of democracy\nare to establish new checks on that democ\nracy.\nThis analysis is not offered as criticism.\nNever before has mankind been faced with\nsuch terrifying facts and portents as those\nevoked by the atomic bomb. To safeguard its\nuse and scientific expansion is, as the May\nbill relates in Section I, necessary to \u201cad\nvance the national welfare, secure the nation\nal defense, insure the national safety and pro\nmote world peace to an extent and by means\nwhich' cannot now be measurd.\u201d And, con\nversely, as the bill also sets forth, \u201cthe mis\nuse of such energy, by design or through\nignorance, may inflict incalculable disaster\nupon the nation, destroy the general welfare,\nimperil the national safety and endanger\nworld peace.\u201d The price to democracy is high,\nbut the excellent tit;zens who drafted the\nmeasure see no prudent way of escaping the\npayment.\nConsequently, the powers given to the Atom\nic Energy Commission and its Administrator,\nestablished by the May bill, and the lim'ta\ntions imposed on science and production are\nwithout\\parallel for operation in time of\npeace. The House Military Affairs Committee\nis going over the measure with utmost care,\nbut, if it is not fundamentally amended, the\nabove statement will stand, as the following\nsummary should make plain.\nThe President, who is given the right to\nappoint the nine members of the Commission\nwith the consent of the Senate, may remove\nany one on the ground that his continuance\nin office \u201cwould be in:mical to the national\ninterest,\u201d and he is not required to document\nthat opinion.\nThe Commission and the Administrator may\nmake any expenditure, of whatever size, they\nmay consider \u2018\u2018necessary to carry out their\nrespective functions,\u201d to the limit of amounts\nwhich Congress and the President may see\nfit to provide, and the General Accounting\nOffice may not \u201cdisallow credit for nor with\nhold funds because of any expenditure which\nthe Commission shall determine and certify\nto have been necessary to carry out the pro\nvisions of the act.\u201d\nThe Commission is directed to follow a pol\nicy of minimum interference with private re\nsearch and enterprise, but it is given plenary\npower over both in any activity that is in,\nor in its opinion may possibly enter, the re\nmote neighborhood of any element of atomic\nenergy. Among its many authorities the Com\nmission may create or organize Government\ncorporations, their stock owned wholly by the\nUnited States, for which no ordinary account\ning need be made. And into its custody a\u2019re\nto be placed all ores, plants, elements, stocks,\nprocesses, technical information and its\nsources, contracts, agreements, leases, pat\nents, application for patents, etc., and \u201cother\nrights of any kind\u201d which, in the Commis\nsion\u2019s view, may be required to carry out its\nassignment. Also, it shall bar at all sources\nany information of such activities as it may\nwish to hold secret so that these cannot be\npublished or otherwise disseminated. And the\npunishment for violation is set at $100,000 or\nten years in jail. t\nUnless the President specifically approves,\nthe Commission and the Administrator shall\nissue no licenses to a foreign Government or\na foreign citizen for the development of any\nactivity in nuclear fision or \u201cthe transmu\ntation of atomic species.\u201d But the Commission\nand the Administrator may license any citi\nzen or company within the jurisdiction of the\nUnited States for any work in these connec\ntions.\nThe Commission can impose any conditions\nit may choose on these license-holders if it\ndeems them \u201cadvisable and appropriate in the\nnational interest.\u201d But, in one of the few\npassages of the bill that puts any limits to\nthe authority bestowed, the Commission and\nthe Administrator are directed to grant their\nlicenses on the basis of equitable treatment\nand wide disribution and in such a manner\nas to \u201cdiscourage the growth of monopoly,\nrestraint of trade and unlawful competition\nin the trades and industries affected.\nHowever, these policies need only be followed\nin so far as they are \u201cfeasible,\u2019\u2019 and the\nCommission and the Administrator are left to\nbe the judges of that.\nThe authorities created by the bill are in\nstructed to interfere as little as possible with\nsmall-scale research, especially by non-pro\nfit laboratories, and to \u201cutilize, encourage and\naid colleges, universities, scientific laborato\nries and hospitals\u201d as much as they can.\nWhen they lease or condemn private property\nthey are told in the May bill to make gener\nous payment, and the owners are given the\nright to sue the United States for larger\namounts if they find the payment unsatis\nfactory, asking 50 per cent of the offer in\nthe meantime without prejudice to their suits.\nAlso, though the Commission and the Admin\nistrator may without tax liability acquire\nState and municipal property on which taxes\nwere being paid, they must fairly reimburse\nthe State and the municipality.\nThese are the outlines of a document which\ndiscloses the first effects of the atomic bomb\non American democracy and the free enter\nprise system.\u2014New York Times.\nEditorial Comment\nNAVAL LOSSES\nRelease by the Navy Department of the full\nlist of our combatant losses at sea during\nthree years and eight months of war provides\nan interesting comparison with a similar list\nof Japanese naval losses made public some\ntime ago. They are much closer, numtrically,\nthan most persons might imagine who had\nnot followed carefully the progress of the\nnaval war in the Pacific.\nJapan lost fifteen aircraft carriers, some of\nthem not much larger than our escort-carrier\nclass, to seven for the United States. Our\nenemy lost four escort carriers to five for\nthe United States in the Pacific. Japan lost\nfourteen heavy cruisers, the United States sev\nen; twenty light cruisers to three for the Unit\ned States; perhaps 100 to 110 destroyers to\nfifty-six destroyers and five destroyer escorts\nin the Pacific for our side and perhaps 100\nsubmarines compared to fifty-two. Only in\nbattleships was there a marked disparity. Ja\npan lost nine of her twelve. The other three\nwere out of commission at war\u2019s end. The\nUnited States lost only the Arizona and the\nOklahoma, both of which were sunk in the\nsneak attack on Pearl Harbor.\u2014New York\nT*\u2014\u25a0\"\nguaranteed to reduce the power to make war\nI eliminates\nHAIISM\nIansKPof\nfRINTOtff\nReconversion Optimism\nChilled By Labor Strife\n\nStrikes Cripple Productioi\nIn Coal, Oil, Steel, Lum\nber Industries\nBY STERLING F. GREEN\nWASHINGTON, Oct. 13\u2014(gb\nTwo months after the peace, Wash\nington\u2019s warm optimism over re\nconversion has chilled in many oi\nficial quarters because of strike\nand work stoppages in basic in\ndustries.\nObjective of the first month fol\nlowing Japanese surrender wa\ncivilian production starting ani\nspurting ahead of schedule.\nKeynote of the second month\nwhich ends tomorrow\u2014was produc\ntion crippled in big segments o\nthe coal, oil, steel and lumber in\ndustries, and threats of stoppage:\nin autos, trucking, shipping an<\nothers.\nReconversion progress still wa:\nconsidered good, in terms of get\nting war debris out of factor'd\nand setting them up for output o:\nthings that boost the nation\u2019s liv\ning standard.\nBut today the government re\nported that requests for strike\nvotes from unions would soar tc\nabout 600 in October, nearlj\ndouble September\u2019s record-break\ning tally of 307.\nMeanwhile the administration\nhad failed in its first big test o1\npersuasion to settle strike cases\nIt resorted to the wartime expedi\nent of seizng 50-odd refineries ir\n15 states to get oil and gas flow\ning.\nAnd government officials discus\nsed, but did ngt act upon, a pro\nposed revision of its wage-price\npolicy to cope with labor\u2019s nation\nwide outcry for 30 per cent higher\nwages to offset loss of war time\nearn ngs.\nBusiness leaders still spoke with\noptimism of expansion and com\ning high employment. In one big\nsurvey only ten large c;ties saw\nno change of rehiring all theii\nlaid-off war workers.\nGovernment went ahead, too,\nwith what it calls \u201cde-control\u201d,\nor knocking the wartime shackles\noff the economy. On Monday these\ncurbs go out the w'ndow:\n1. The ban on construction oi\nnew homes, stores, office and\nhotel buildings, and public works;\nalso, the price lid on new dwell\nings.\n2. All remain\u2019ng priorities on\nairplane passenger travel.\nYet the new mood of caution was\nreflected in most of these develop\nments of the second peacetime\nmonth.\nRations: The government mov\ned warily.\nMeat rationing probably will\ncontinue after Nov. 1; shoes will\ngo off the list then only if produc\ntion jumps as it failed to do in\nSeptember; sugar outlook unchang\ned.\nPrices: The government held the\nline.\nOPA clung to its policy of\nbringing new washers, ironers\nand other long-sought gadgets back\nat 1942 prices. Radios\u20143.500,000\nof them by Christmas\u2014will reach\nthe consumer at that price level.\nWages: The government stood\npat.\nPresident Truman reaffirmed his\npolicy of allowing general wage\nboosts only where no price increase\nresults.\nBut aides of reconversion direct\nor John W. Snyder pressed him\nto declare for a 10 to 15 per cent\nncraase. They say it would push\nI prices up only 2 or 2 1-2 per cent\nthat reconversion can be speede<\nif the government takes the lea(\ninstead of letting unions ant\nmanagement fight it out on th<\npicket lines. Snyder has not budg\ned.\nGoods:\nRefrigerators, washers and ra\ndios began to appear as dealers\nsamples. Most major auto maker!\n5 were in or near production. Tex\ntiles improved, but officials be\ngan to investigate why more low\ncost garments had failed to shov\ns up.\nI Jobs: The government was en\ncouraged.\nUnemployment climbed above\nthe 2,000,000 mark, but 700,000 jobs\nE were going begging as laid-of:\nworkers shopped around. Abou\ni one-third of those discharged die\nI not seek jobless pay.\nYet the government warned thai\nhigh unemployment will persisi\nthrough 1946 because industry\ncannot expand fast enough to keej\nup with army and navy discharges\nIndustry people say many wai\nworkers apparently have dropped\nout of the labor market, but may\ncome back later.\nLETTER BOX\nWHY HE RE-ENLISTED\nSergt. Heinz Grohman served sever\nyears in the Army, partly with the\nFirst Allied Airborne Army in Europe\nand participated in five campaigns, spent\nforty-eight days as a civilian seeking a\njob that would support himself, his wife\nand his child. Unable to find one, h\u00ab\nhas re-enlisted in the Army and writ\nten this letter, as he says, so that men\ncoming home from overseas service may\nknow what they face.\u2014The Editor.\nTo the Editor:\nMy story is very short. Some\npeople will agree with me and\nI was discharged under the point\nsystem. I got out of the Army\nAugust 19. I took a two-week va\ncation and started to look for work.\nThe best I vas offered was $35 a\nweek. With a wife and child, that\u2019s\nnot too good.\nMy best offer was the Wilming\nton Police department. I was\ntreated like a man by Chief Cas\nteen and the lieutenants and ser\ngeants of the force. I thank them\nfor their kindness and good treat\nment. Unfortunately there were no\nopenings till the first of the year,\nbut I was pretty sure of getting\non a very good police force.\nBut I needed a job till there\nwould be a vacancy. So I went\nout to the North Carolina Ship\nbuilding company. I was told that\nI would have to start at the low\nest wages. I worked on the guard\nforce under Chief Kennel. I thought\nI would try it. 1 worked one\nmonth, I was getting 74 cents an\nhour.\nI say that a man who has been\nfighting for his country should be\nable to get the same wages on an\nunskilled joh as the man who has\nbeen working on the same job for\nthree years. Yet I talked with one\nshipyard common laborer who was\ngetting 92 cents ah hour.\nI don\u2019t know whether it matters,\nbut we men who went over can\u2019t\nhelp that we had to leave jobs at\nhome; but we sure did think while\nwe were over there that we could\nrate the same wages as the man\nwho stayed behind doing his part\nover here\nM/SGT. HEINZ GROHMAN\nWilmington, N. C.\nOctober 13, 1945.\nThe Bank of England is 251\nyears old.\nSCOUTMASTERS\u2019\nCOURSE SLATED\nWilmington\u2019s first training course\nfor Scoutmasters in two years will\nI begin at the American Legion\n1 home, Third' and Dock streets,\nWednesday night at 7:30 p.m., ac\ncording to an anouncement yester\nday by the Rev. Mortimer Glover,\nleadership training chairman.\nH. W. Winkle is Scoutmaster of\nthe course, J. M. Thomas, senior\npatrol leader, Carroll Tinsley, jun\nior assistant Scoutmaster, and Joe\nBarnes, quartermaster.\nAssistant Scoutmasters each\nweek will include C. E. Goody\nkoontz, Wallace West, F. S. Pas\nchall, W. S. Cheaves, Royal L.\nMercer, C. W. Baker, E. H. Kend\nrick, C. L. Bethea, W. P. Jones,\ni E. M. McEachern, R. Brookes\nPeters, R. J. Divine, B. L. Pringg,\nR. B. Howard, the Rev. Kermt\nWheeler, and E. L. Croxton\nPatrol leaders will be Frank\nJones, Jack Towell, Ben Jones, L.\nD, Harrelson, R. H. Mann, C. R.\nJohnston, Jr., Ed Howard, and\nJ; B. Sellers.\nOthers expected to attend the\ncourse include George Tenuta,\nJack Craig, J. W. Perm enter, John\nConway, G. Y. Warwick, E. Z.\nBlanton, F. D. Love, Lawrence\nBowen, Frank McCall, R. M. Pad\nrick, Sam Houston, Claud O\u2019\nShields, Albert Wells, John Gym\ntruk, Bernard App ,the Rev. Wil\nliam A. Pool, C. Louis Shields,\nMcKoy Southerland, W. Z. Cor\nbett, Earl Biggs, Ed Allard, the\nRev. John H. Long, Macon Worn\nble, Bruce Biggs, M. W. Gore, J.\nV. Stanley, J. A. Thackston, Walter\nWinn and C. W. Garrett.\nAll t\"AAne +a Ko AY*rto\u00abi7orf\nin the Together Plan have com\npleted step five of the eight steps\nin organizing a troop, according\nto the Rev. Walter B. Freed,\norganization chairman.\nA \"Get Acquainted with Scout\ning\u201d conference has been held at\nSouthside Baptist church, Wesley\nMemorial church, Brigade Boys\u2019\nclub, Cape Fear Presbyterian\nchurch, and St. Mary\u2019s Catholic\nchurch, the Rev. Mr. Freed re\nported.\nThe next step is to hold a troop\nmeeting, and each sponsoring in\nstitution plans to do that next\nweek. In the meanwhile, the new\nleaders will begin their training\nat the Scoutmasters\u2019 Training\ncourse.\nThe Rev. Mr. Freed expressed\nthe opinion that all these troops\nshould be registered before the\nend of the month.\nLocal Man Jailed In\nAssault Attempt Case\nBenjamin Huffman, 47-year-old\nship caulker, 527 South Front\nstreet, was arrested by city police\nyesterday on charges of, assault\nwith intent to commit criminal as\nsault on a seven-year-old girl.\nFailing to furnish $1,500 bond,\nHuffman was lodged in the New\nHanover county jail. He is sched\nuled to appear before Judge H.\nWinfield Smith in Recorder\u2019s court\nfor a preliminary hearing at 10\no\u2019clock tomorrow morning.\nWILL HEAD BOND DRIVE\nNEW BERN, Oct. 13.-John G.\nDunn, Jr., assistant secretary\ntreasurer of -the New Bern Morris\nPlan company and the New Bern\nBuilding and Loan association, will\nserve as Craven county\u2019s campaign\nchairman during the Victory Loan\ndrive which will open October 29\nthroughout the nation, it has been\nannounced by Leo H. Harvey, of\nKinston, regional chairman of the\nstate finance committee. j\nInterpreting\nThe News\nBy JAMES D. WHITE\nAssociated Press Staff Writer\nWRITER\nSAN FRANCISCO, Oct 13- a _\nThere\u2019s a rumor going around Tn\nShanghai that China is about t*\nmove her capital back to Peiping\nin the dusty north, from Nanking\nin the hot and humid south.\nThat would be something Uke\nmoving the capital of the United\nStates\u2014if it were at Mobile, \\'a\"\nto its present site at Washu,gtw7\nD. C.\nClimate would be involved, but\nalso would be politics and the fu.\nture.\nThe same report was current in\nthis country a couple of years ago,\nIt came from sources close\nChiang Kai-shek, who at that time\nwas said to be convinced that it\nwould be a good thing to have a\ncapital close to Manchuria v.i cn\nthat important industrial base v as\nrecaptured.\nSYMBOL\nPeiping used to be called Pc king,\nmeaning Northern Capital. As such\nit was a symbol to Chinese of tne\nManchus who established their ai\nien court there in 1644. After the\nChinese revolution in 1911, Peking\nbecame also a symbol of the de.\ncadent Chinese Republican regime\nwhich appeased Japanese aggres\nsion. So in 1927 the Nationalists un\nder Chiang Kai-shek took the cap.\nital to Nanking and renamed the\nRepublican capital Peiping, or\nNorthern Peace.\nAfter the Japanese surrender this\nSeptember, General Ho Ying-chin,\nthe Southerner who is Chiang Kai\nshek\u2019s Chief of Staff, announced\nthat China\u2019s government would re\nturn to Nanking from Chungking,\nits wartime refuge, by the end of\nthis year.\nmow anangnai rumor revives the\nhardy report to the contrary, that\nthe capital is going back to the\nnorth. If it does, it will be became\nof high reasons of economic and\npolitical policy.\nNearly all of China\u2019s industry is\nin Manchuria and most of her\nstrategic minerals, including iron\nand coal, are either there or in\nNorth China.\nChinese Communism is strongest\nin the north, and if the government\nwere to move back there it would\nbe a bold reassertion of authority\nwhich could gain it great and\nmuch-needed prestige.\nWOULD REDUCE INFLUENCE\nChinese banking influence center\ning in Shanghai was strong in near\nby Nanking. In Peipig that influ\nence, as well as that of British,\nAmerican and French commerical\ninterest, would likely be reduced.\nPossibly most important, return,\ning to Peiping the Chinese govern\nment would be moving diplomatic\nally as well as geographically clos\ner to Soviet Russia.\nThe new Chinese treaties with\nRussia provide a foundation upon\nwhich a firm Russo-Chine coopera\ntion might be built, perhaps closer\nthan China ever built with Britain\nor America. Through those treat\nies, Russia obtains an important\npartnership in Manchuria which is\nto last 30 years.\nIf China and Russia are to get\nalong, they will work out their key\nproblems there, in the north.\nNanking was chosen in 1927 by\nsouthern and central Chinese under\nChiang Kai-shek. Around him now\nare important Northerners like\nChang Chih-chung, Sun Lien-chung,\nand Shang Chen.\nChiang\u2019s most immediate eco\nnomic problem is to recover and\nexploit the industry of Manchuria.\nHis biggest domestic problem is the\nChinese Communist problem in the\nnorth. His biggest foreign relations\nproblem is with Russia. His pro\nblems, and the inclination he has\nto tackle them indirectly, may lead\nhim and his government back north\nagain to Peiping.\nAs Peking, it was China\u2019s capi\ntal when China was greatest. It\nwould likely be called Peking\nagain.\n307 STRIKE VOTES\nASKED BY UNIONS\nWASHINGTON, Oct. 13 UP)\nLabor unions filed a record-break*\ning total of 307 requests for strike\nvotes in September and this\nmonth\u2019s tally may hit 600, the Na\ntional Labor Relations board re\nported tonight.\nSome NLRB office* U* 4oin|\nnothing but taking strike polls, the\nagency said, \u201cto the exclusion of\nhandling any reconversion ques\ntions of bargaining rights and un\nfair labor practices.\u201d\nThe voting results, in the first\nfull month of peace, showed work\ners supporting strikes 8 to 1.\nThe report, the first issued by\nNLRB on strike ballots taken un\nder the Smith-Connally act, nie\none day after several congress on\nal leaders spoke out in favor of\nrepeal of that measure.\nThe act requires NLRB to take\na str;ke vote, upon a union s re\nquest, after a 30-day interval. In\nstead of being the \u2018\u2018cooling c\u201c\ndevice it was intended to be, crit\nics say it implies a government\nsanction for strikes if the work s\nvote for them.\nChairman May (D-Ky), of 5\nhouse military committee, said\nfavored repeal and wished to s\u2019 t\nhearing on that question as soon\nas possible.\nSeptember\u2019s total of requests\nfor strike votes was more than 50\nper cent higher than the prev: s\npeak, the 196 filed in June,\nUruguay produces no cr d'","height":"27280","width":"20680"}}
